  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provide improved lifesaving emergency referral services, including psychiatric treatment, psychotherapy and physical rehabilitation services in Telafar and Sinjar hospitals of Ninawa governorate</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IDP, Returnee and Host community, 9882 beneficiaries (4489 Men, 1350 Boys, 2874 Women, 1169 Girls)</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project is designed to respond to the needs of the vulnerable targeted returnees dis-aggregated by age group and gender, especially women and adolescent girls (+ 12 years old) who are more prone for GBV and Psychosocial suffering. 
                                     
Qualified staff have been solicited from the area targeted, selected applicants have been interviewed, background checked, hired and contracts were signed. Several trainings for all staff (MHPSS service providers and non MHPSS service providers) on MHPSS, PFA, PSS, GBV prevention &amp; response, MH gap and PM+ were done by Cordaid and WHO. The recruited staff also were trained on referral and case management, data collection, and internal policies including confidentiality, code of conduct, do no-harm guidelines, safety and security. The field staff includes psychiatrists, social workers, CHWs, community members, orthopaedics, physiotherapists and assistants. All the mentioned staff is supervised by Program Manager, Program Coordinator, Project Protection Officer and MEAL Officer of Cordaid.

More than 8,507 beneficiaries have received MHPSS, PSS, GBV and PR services in Telafar and Sinjar since January 2019 till end of October 2019.
 
This project will integrate MHPSS and PR into the work of Secondary Health Care Centres Telefar and Sinjar in a sustainable manner through Cordaid support. US$416,440.50 is requested for a one-year project implementation.
In line with the Iraqi government and health cluster priorities, Cordaid incorporates capacity building of the staff of the two hospitals directly into the program design. Cordaid will also advocate with the government stakeholders and the international community (for policies, practice and funds) for the provision of MHPSS and PR in Iraq in accordance with international standards. 

While the needs for MHPSS, PSS, GBV and PR will continue beyond the proposed grant, Cordaid (with the support of WHO) will provide capacity building in order for services to continue after the end of the project</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">a)	Continuous provision of a comprehensive package of mental health services by improving the capacity of MHPSS actors, healthcare- and humanitarian workers to increase their response to GBV. 
b)	Continuous provision of services for people with disabilities: basic physical rehabilitation, screening and referral services in Sinjar and Telafar.</narrative>
  </description>
